WorldStage Newsonline--- The United Nations (UN) has called for the immediate and unconditional release of all missing Dopchi schoolgirls who were abducted by Boko Haram in Yobe on Feb. 19. The Secretary-General, Mr Antonio Guterres, said in a statement by his Spokesperson, Mr Stephane Dujarric expressed outrage at the abduction of 110 schoolgirls of Government Girls Technical College, Dapchi, Yobe, by the  suspected Boko Haram terrorists. Guterres said he was gravely concerned over the situation of the schoolgirls’ abducted during an attack on their educational institution. The UN chief urged the Nigerian authorities to swiftly bring those responsible for this dastardly act to justice. Guterres reiterated the solidarity and support of the UN to Nigerian Government and other affected countries in the region in their fight against terrorism and violent extremism. The UN had earlier described the abduction as “another horrific incident where young women and girls are targeted by terror groups”. “And we very much hope that the perpetrators will be brought to justice, and just as importantly, that the girls will be found and returned to safety,” he said.